%description:
Module test for TI-LFA (RFC 9855) backup activation (Workstream F2, Phase 4): exercises the
Phase-1 data-plane backup fields (LibTable::setBackup()/activateBackup(), resolveLabel()'s
backupActive branch) against an ACTUAL live packet, not just the EV_INFO log lines
srmpls_tilfa_repair_pq.test already asserts. Every existing TI-LFA test locks in either the
repair COMPUTATION (srmpls_tilfa_repair_pq.test, srmpls_tilfa_repair_bridge.test) or the
activation/revert EV_INFO lines (srmpls_tilfa_repair_pq.test's Phase-3 half) -- none of them
had ever pushed a single real packet through the installed backup label stack. This test closes
that gap with the narrowest observable that actually depends on the backup mechanism: the
label stack Mpls::doStackOps() logs at A's own LIB lookup for a live, in-flight packet.

Topology: hostA -- U -- A -- { B -- D (metric 1+1+1=3), C -- D (metric 1+1+1=3, tied) } -- D --
hostD (U=9.9.9.9, A=1.1.1.1, B=2.2.2.2, C=3.3.3.3, D=4.4.4.4; srgbBase 16000). U is the SR
INGRESS: its SrPolicy classifies traffic to hostD's subnet onto the unconstrained node-SID
segment "node:4" (label 16004) and pushes it. A is deliberately kept OUT of that ingress role
and carries no policies of its own -- A is a pure TRANSIT hop for this flow (and the PLR
protecting the A-B link). This split matters: SrPolicy.cc's own resolveSegmentList() resolves
its first hop directly via SegmentRouting::resolveNextHop() and documents that "ingress-
classified traffic never consults the LIB at all" -- so if A itself were the ingress (as an
earlier version of this test had it), the packets IT let A originates would never touch
LibTable::resolveLabel() at all, and the backupActive branch this test exists to exercise would
silently never run. Only a packet arriving at A ALREADY label-encoded (i.e. one that went
through a genuine upstream ingress first) forces A to do a real LIB lookup for label 16004,
which is exactly where setBackup()/activateBackup() take effect.

What makes this test discriminating rather than redundant with srmpls_tilfa_repair_pq.test:
recomputeAndInstall() (triggered synchronously by the SAME event that detects the A-B failure)
already reprograms A's node-SID(D) entry to route via C -- in THIS model, ordinary recompute
alone would deliver every packet with zero loss even if handleOwnLinkStateChange() were a
no-op, since nothing here measures a convergence GAP. A "packets still arrive" or "no delivery
gap" assertion would therefore pass whether or not the backup mechanism does anything at all,
and is deliberately NOT the primary assertion here (see Workstream F2's plan and this
workstream's docs for that limitation). What genuinely depends on
handleOwnLinkStateChange()/LibTable's backupActive branch is WHICH label stack A applies to a
live TRANSIT packet while the backup is active: with backupActive=true, resolveLabel() returns
tiLfaRepairByRouter[D] = a single node-SID PUSH of C's label (16003) -- an EXTRA, OUTER push
stacked on top of the packet's still-present, unmodified inner node-SID(D) label 16004 (SR
repair semantics: the packet keeps carrying its ultimate destination's own segment underneath a
temporary detour segment) -- so "doStackOps: {PUSH 16003}" appearing in A's own log, while (and
only while) TI-LFA reports the backup active, is a real, packet-level exercise of the Phase-1
backup data plane, not an artifact of ordinary recompute (which would instead re-SWAP A's
node-SID(D) entry, never PUSH 16003 there at all).

At t=1s a ~ScenarioManager severs the A-B link (as in srmpls_tilfa_repair_pq.test); at t=2s it
is restored. Traffic runs continuously across both transitions.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: test.ned

import inet.node.inet.StandardHost;
import inet.node.mpls.SrMplsRouter;
import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import ned.DatarateChannel;

network TiLfaTrafficTest
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    types:
        channel Link extends DatarateChannel
        {
            datarate = 1Mbps;
            delay = 10us;
        }
    submodules:
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager;
        hostA: StandardHost {
            @display("p=50,150");
        }
        U: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "9.9.9.9";
                peers = "ppp1"; // ppp0 goes to hostA, not an IGP peer
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                policies = xmldoc("policiesU.xml");
                @display("p=180,150");
            gates:
                pppg[2];
        }
        A: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "1.1.1.1";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1 ppp2";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                segmentRouting.tiLfa = true;
                @display("p=310,150");
            gates:
                pppg[3];
        }
        B: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "2.2.2.2";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                @display("p=440,80");
            gates:
                pppg[2];
        }
        C: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "3.3.3.3";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                @display("p=440,220");
            gates:
                pppg[2];
        }
        D: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "4.4.4.4";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1"; // ppp2 goes to hostD, not an IGP peer
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                @display("p=570,150");
            gates:
                pppg[3];
        }
        hostD: StandardHost {
            @display("p=700,150");
        }
    connections:
        hostA.pppg++ <--> Link <--> U.pppg[0];
        U.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> A.pppg[0];
        A.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> B.pppg[0]; // primary: metric 1
        B.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> D.pppg[0]; // metric 1
        A.pppg[2] <--> Link <--> C.pppg[0]; // alternate: metric 1 (tied with primary)
        C.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> D.pppg[1]; // metric 1
        D.pppg[2] <--> Link <--> hostD.pppg++;
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: sidtable.xml
<sr>
    <node router="1.1.1.1" sid="1"/>
    <node router="2.2.2.2" sid="2"/>
    <node router="3.3.3.3" sid="3"/>
    <node router="4.4.4.4" sid="4"/>
</sr>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: policiesU.xml
<policies>
    <policy dest="10.0.9.30" netmask="255.255.255.255" segments="node:4"/>
</policies>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: scenario.xml
<scenario>
    <at t="1s">
        <disconnect src-module="A" src-gate="pppg$o[1]"/>
        <disconnect src-module="B" src-gate="pppg$o[0]"/>
    </at>
    <at t="2s">
        <connect src-module="A" src-gate="pppg[1]"
                 dest-module="B" dest-gate="pppg[0]"
                 channel-type="ned.DatarateChannel">
            <param name="delay" value="10us"/>
            <param name="datarate" value="1Mbps"/>
        </connect>
    </at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostA.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
default:	10.0.9.2	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: U.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.9.3	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: A.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.4	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.9.5	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.9.7	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: B.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.6	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.9.9	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: C.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.8	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.9.11	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: D.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.10	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.9.12	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.9.13	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostD.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.9.30	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
default:	10.0.9.13	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: omnetpp.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = TiLfaTrafficTest
sim-time-limit = 3s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
**.cmdenv-log-level = "info"
output-scalar-file = "${resultdir}/${configname}-#${runnumber}.sca"

**.hostA.numApps = 1
**.hostA.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.hostA.app[0].localPort = 100
**.hostA.app[0].destPort = 100
**.hostA.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.hostA.app[0].startTime = 0.2s
**.hostA.app[0].sendInterval = 0.01s
**.hostA.app[0].destAddresses = "hostD"

**.hostD.numApps = 1
**.hostD.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.hostD.app[0].localPort = 100

**.hostA.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostA.rt"
**.hostD.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostD.rt"
**.U.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "U.rt"
**.A.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "A.rt"
**.B.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "B.rt"
**.C.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "C.rt"
**.D.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "D.rt"

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Before the failure: U's SrPolicy ingress push puts the unconstrained node-SID (D=16004) on
%# every packet, exactly as sr_reroute.test's identical setup shows
%contains: stdout
doStackOps: {PUSH 16004}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The failure is actually injected
%contains: stdout
Disconnecting TiLfaTrafficTest.A.pppg$o[1]
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# TI-LFA activates the precomputed backup for D as soon as A's link to B (2.2.2.2) dies
%contains: stdout
TI-LFA: activated backup for 4.4.4.4 (protected link to 2.2.2.2 went down)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The discriminating assertion: a LIVE, already label-encoded packet arriving at A (a genuine
%# TRANSIT lookup, since U -- not A -- is the SR ingress) now gets an outer PUSH of C's node-SID
%# (16003) stacked on top of the still-present inner 16004 -- something ordinary (non-backup)
%# node-SID forwarding at A never does (that path only ever SWAPs 16004, it never pushes 16003).
%# This can only happen via LibTable::resolveLabel()'s backupActive branch actually being taken
%# for a real packet.
%contains: stdout
doStackOps: {PUSH 16003}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# ... and reverts once the A-B link comes back up
%contains: stdout
TI-LFA: reverted backup for 4.4.4.4 (protected link to 2.2.2.2 came back up)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Traffic keeps flowing throughout (a coarse sanity check, not a convergence-gap measurement --
%# see this file's description for why a precise zero-gap assertion wouldn't actually be
%# discriminating in this model): hostD receives a large, still-climbing count by the end
%postrun-command: grep "TiLfaTrafficTest.hostD.app\[0\] packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '{ if ($NF+0 > 200) print "HOSTD_KEEPS_FLOWING", $0 }' > hostd.out
%contains: hostd.out
HOSTD_KEEPS_FLOWING
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
